Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service

Numbers reduced substantially this week as agents offered 936 liveweight cattle. Female cattle again made up the bulk of the offering that included 289 cows, 239 heifers and 388 steers. Quality was again mixed with 2 score cattle well represented. The usual trade and processor buyers, feeders and restockers were active across the offering in a sale that returned mixed results.

Vealer steers and heifers eased 30c to 50c/kg as steers sold from 200c to 320c with heifers fetching 207c to 301c/kg. Yearling steers and heifers also eased by 10c to 30c/kg with steers selling from 200c to 349c while heifers ranged from 181c to 321c/kg.

A small selection of manufacturing steers saw dairy breeds selling from 167c to 270c with beef breeds fetching 290c to 310c/kg. Grown steers and heifers improved by 15c to 40c/kg as steers sold from 267c to 359c with heifers ranging from 180c to 343c/kg.

Another good selection of cows sold mostly 10c to 20c dearer than the previous sale with light dairy cows selling from 40c to 80c/kg and beef types 140c to 240c/kg. Medium weight beef cows sold from 229c to 289c with dairy types fetching 80c to 171c/kg. Heavy beef cows sold from 187c to 327c as dairy types ranged from 170c to 271c/kg. Bulls sold from 230c to 300c/kg.

Market reporter: John Traeger.
